Problem

Did you know women on average makes 11% less than their male co-workers in Ontario? With soaring cost of living everywhere, young women may face more financial challenges.

The traditional budgeting apps heavily rely on vigilant user behavior alone and this may not be appealing for many people. So how do we motivate young women to achieve their financial goals and maintain it?

Research

Research by HSBC has revealed that 44% of working women in Canada struggle with paying bills and 51% doesnâ€™t know how much they need to save for retirement. Many budgeting apps have limited or no financial health and goal related features to help people save.

Freemium service models may negatively impact userbase by locking useful features behind a paywall. Our team decided to focus on these issues to help young women reach for better financial stability.

Shortcomings

Ads & Premium service tier

Lacking financial health feature

No free service

Can't track spending

Limitation on free version

Ads and other solicitation

Our Solutions

No Ads or Premium service tier

Flexibility to set and track goals

Customized incentives for motivation

Design

The user experience is augmented by gamified loop that provides rewards and incentives for good financial behaviour by achieving their goals.
